window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"FINAL","topic":"DERIVED QUANTITIES AND DIMENSIONAL ANALYSIS :","question":"The force, F, acting on the wings of an aircraft moving through air of velocity, v, and density, \u03c1, is given by the equation F = kvx\u03c1yAz, where k is a dimensionless constant and A is the surface area of the wings of the aircraft. Use dimensional analysis to determine the values of x, y and z.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"F = kvx\u03c1yAz    For the left hand side:    F = mass \u00d7 acceleration = MLT-2    For the right hand side:    v = LT-1, \u03c1 = ML-3 and A = L2    So,    MLT-2 = k(LT-1)x(ML-3)y(L2)z    Since k is dimensionless,    MLT-2 = (LT-1)x(ML-3)y(L2)z    MLT-2 = Lx \u00d7 T(-1)x \u00d7 My \u00d7 L(-3)y \u00d7 L(2)z    MLT-2 = Lx \u00d7 T-x \u00d7 My \u00d7 L-3y \u00d7 L2z    MLT-2 = Lx - 3y + 2z \u00d7 T-x \u00d7 My    M1L1T-2 = Lx - 3y + 2z \u00d7 T-x \u00d7 My    Comparing the powers:    For M,     y = 1    For L,    x - 3y + 2z = 1 ---- (i)    For T,    -x = -2    \u2234 x = 2    Substitute (2) for x and (1) for y in equation (i)    \u21d2 2 - 3(1) + 2z = 1    \u21d2 2 - 3 + 2z = 1    \u21d2 -1 + 2z = 1    \u21d2 2z = 1 + 1    \u21d2 2z = 2    \u2234 z = 1    Hence, x = 2, y = 1 and z = 1.","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>2>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"Define strain energy.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Strain energy is the potential energy stored within an elastic material as a result of its deformation caused by external forces.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>2>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"Write an expression for the energy stored, E, in a stretched wire of original length,  l , cross-sectional area, A, extension, e, and Young's modulus, Y, of the material of the wire.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Energystoredinaspring,E=12Fe  Stress=ForceArea=FA  Strain=extensionLength=el  Young'smodulus,Y=stressstrain=F/Ae/l  Y=FA\u00f7el=FA\u00d7le  Y=FlAe\u21d2F=YAel  Now,  E=12\u00d7(YAel)\u00d7e  \u2234E=YAe22l","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>3>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PROJECTILE MOTION :","question":"A projectile is fired at an angle, \u03b8, to the horizontal with velocity, u. Show that at any time, t, during the motion, the:    horizontal component of the velocity is independent of t;","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From v = u + gt:  ux = ucos\u03b8, g = 0 (horizontal component is not affected by gravity)  vx = ucos\u03b8 + (0)t  \u2234 vx =  ucos\u03b8","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>3>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PROJECTILE MOTION :","question":"A projectile is fired at an angle, \u03b8, to the horizontal with velocity, u. Show that at any time, t, during the motion, the:  vertical component of the velocity depends on t.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"vy = uy - gt  \u2234 vy = usin\u03b8 - gt","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>3>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PROJECTILE MOTION :","question":"State the assumption on which projectile motion is based.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"It assumes that the only force acting on the projectile is gravity, and there are no other forces, such as air resistance or drag, affecting its motion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SATELLITES AND ROCKETS :","question":"State three differences between geostationary satellites and polar satellites.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Geostationary satellites orbit the Earth at the same speed as the rotation of the Earth itself and are therefore seen as stationary, while polar satellites orbit the Earth at various speeds.    - Geostationary satellites provide continuous coverage of a fixed area on the surface of the Earth, while polar satellites offer global coverage as they move from pole to pole.    - Geostationary satellites generally have a higher altitude than polar satellites.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>5>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"Using the kinetic theory, explain the term diffusion of fluid molecules.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"According to the kinetic theory, diffusion in fluids occurs because of the random and continuous motion of molecules. This motion results in a net movement of the molecules from regions of higher concentration to regions to regions of lower concentration ultimately leading to the mixing of substances in the fluid i.e. the process continues until the concentration becomes uniform throughout the fluid. It's driven by the kinetic energy of the molecules and leads to the mixing of substances in fluids.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>5>b>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : SOURCES OF LIGHT","question":"Name one phenomenon that demonstrates that light behaves as a:    wave;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Interference of light waves","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>5>b>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"WAVE-PARTICLE PARADOX : DUALITY OF MATTER","question":"Name one phenomenon that demonstrates that light behaves as a:  particle.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Photo-electric effect  - Compton Effect","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>6>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF MATTER :","question":"State one difference between an intrinsic and an extrinsic semiconductor.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Extrinsic semiconductors are produced by adding impurities into pure semiconductors, while intrinsic semiconductors are always present in their most pure state.  - Extrinsic semiconductors have a high electrical conductivity in comparison to other materials at room temperature, while intrinsic semiconductors have a low electrical conductivity.  - In intrinsic semiconductors, the number of electrons and holes is equal, however, this is not the case in extrinsic semiconductors.  - Temperature alone determines the behaviour of intrinsic semiconductors, whereas extrinsic semiconductors are influenced by both temperature and the number of impurities present.  - n-type and p-type semiconductors are two categories of extrinsic semiconductors,while intrinsic semiconductors are not further subdivided.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>6>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CIRCUIT","question":"Draw a circuit diagram to illustrate full wave smoothing rectification.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>7>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FIBRE OPTICS :","question":"What is fibre optics?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Fiber optics is a technology that uses light to transmit data over long distances. Fiber optic cables are made of thin, flexible strands of glass or plastic that can carry a large amount of data at very high speeds.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 1>7>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FIBRE OPTICS :","question":"State two reasons why optical fibres are preferred to copper cables in the telecommunication industry.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Higher bandwidth: Optical fibers can carry a much larger amount of data than copper cables. This is because light travels much faster than electricity, and optical fibers can carry more light signals than copper cables can carry electrical signals.  - Longer distances: Optical fibers can transmit data over longer distances than copper cables without signal loss. This is because light signals are less attenuated in optical fibers than electrical signals are in copper cables.  - Immunity to interference: Optical fibers are immune to electrical interference, which can cause problems with copper cables. This is because optical fibers transmit light signals, which are not affected by electrical fields.  - Security: Optical fibers are more secure than copper cables because they are difficult to tap. This is because light signals cannot be detected without damaging the optical fiber.  - Durability: Optical fibers are more durable than copper cables. They are less susceptible to damage from moisture, temperature fluctuations, and physical impact.  - Cost-effectiveness: Optical fibers are becoming more cost-effective than copper cables, especially for high-bandwidth applications. This is because the cost of manufacturing optical fibers has decreased significantly in recent years.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>8>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)","question":"State the reason why simple harmonic motion is periodic.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Simple harmonic motion is periodic because of the restoring force which is proportional to the displacement, acts in opposite direction to the motion.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>8>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"State two factors that affect the period of oscillation of a simple pendulum.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Length of the pendulum  - Strength of the gravitational field","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>8>a>iii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : APPLICATION OF MECHANICAL ENERGY","question":"Sketch a graph of the total mechanical energy, E, against displacement, y, for the motion of a simple pendulum from one extreme position to the other.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>8>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF WORK","question":"The diagram below illustrates an oscillatory pendulum.    Calculate the work done in raising the pendulum to point B, if the mass of the bob is 50 g.   [g = 10 ms-2]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"m = 50 g = 0.05 kg, g = 10 ms-2, h = 10 cm = 0.1 m, P.E = ?  P.E = mgh = 0.05 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 0.1  \u2234 P.E = 0.05 J","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>8>c","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"A spiral spring of spring constant, k, and natural length,  l , has a scale pan of mass 0.04 kg hanging on its lower end while the upper end is firmly fixed to a support. When an object of mass 0.20 kg is placed on the scale pan, the length of the spring becomes 0.055 m and when the object is replaced with another object of mass 0.28 kg, the length of the spring becomes 0.065 m. Calculate the values of k and  l .   [g = 10 ms-2]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let the extension be  \u2206l   F = k \u2206l  = k( ln  -  l )   where k is the spring constant,  ln  is the new length,  l  is the natural length and F = mg.  Total mass = mass of pan + added mass  For the first case,  m1 = 0.04 + 0.20 = 0.24 kg  F1 = 0.24 \u00d7 10 = 2.4 N   \u2206l  = 0.055 -  l   Since F = k \u2206l ,  2.4 = k(0.055 -  l )  2.4 = 0.055k -  l k --- (i)  For the second case,  m2 = 0.04 + 0.28 = 0.32 kg  F2 = 0.32 \u00d7 10 = 3.2 N   \u2206l  = 0.065 -  l   Since F = k \u2206l ,  3.2 = k(0.065 -  l )  3.2 = 0.065k -  l k --- (ii)  Subtracting equation (i) from (ii)  \u21d2 0.8 = 0.01k  \u2234k=0.80.01=80Nm-1  Substitute (80) for k in equation (i)  \u21d2 2.4 = 0.055(80) - 80 l   \u21d2 2.4 = 4.4 - 80 l   \u21d2 80 l  = 4.4 - 2.4  \u21d2 80 l  = 2  \u2234 l =280=0.025m  Therefore, the value of k = 80 Nm-1 and  l  = 0.025 m","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>9>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"Define each of the following terms used with simple machines:    pivot;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A pivot, often referred to as a fulcrum, is the point or axis around which a simple machine, such as a lever or a seesaw, rotates.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>9>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"Define each of the following terms used with simple machines:  load;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A load is the object or weight that is being moved, lifted, or supported by the machine.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>9>a>iii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"Define each of the following terms used with simple machines:  efficiency.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Efficiency refers to how effectively a machine can perform its intended task while minimizing energy loss. The efficiency formula is often given as:    Efficiency(%)=Useful Output WorkInput Work\u00d7100%","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>9>b>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF WORK","question":"A truck of mass 1.2 \u00d7 103 kg is pulled from rest by a constant horizontal force of 25.2 N on a levelled road. If the maximum speed attainable in the process is 60 kmh-1.  Calculate the:    work done by the force;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"m=1.2\u00d7103kg,u=0,F=25.2N,v=60kmh-1=16.67ms-1,W=?  Work=\u2206K.E=K.E2-K.E1  \u21d2Work=12mv2-12mu2  \u21d2Work=12m(v2-u2)  \u21d2Work=12x1200x(16.672-02)  \u21d2Work=600x(277.89-0)  \u21d2Work=600x277.89  \u2234Work=1.67x105J","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>9>b>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW","question":"A truck of mass 1.2 \u00d7 103 kg is pulled from rest by a constant horizontal force of 25.2 N on a levelled road. If the maximum speed attainable in the process is 60 kmh-1.  Calculate the:  distance travelled by the truck in reaching the maximum speed.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"F=ma\u21d2a=Fm  a=25.21.2 \u00d7 103=0.021ms-2  Fromv2=u2+2as,  s=v2 - u22a=16.672 - 022 \u00d7 0.021  \u2234s=6616.4m=6.62km","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>9>c","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"State two differences between absolute zero temperature and ice point.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Absolute zero temperature is the lowest possible temperature that theoretically represents the complete absence of thermal energy while the ice point is the temperature at water coexists with ice in thermal equilibrium.  - Absolute zero temperature is defined as 0 Kelvin (0 K) or approximately -273.15oC while ice point is typically defined as 0oC at sea level.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>9>d","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"FINAL","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"An uncalibrated liquid-in-glass thermometer was used in determining a Celsius temperature. The readings are tabulated below.    Temperature/oC-60100Length of column/cmL2.015.0  Determine the value of L.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"0 - (-6)2 - L=100 - 015 - 2  \u21d262 - L=10013  \u21d26\u00d713=100(2-L)  \u21d278=200-100L  \u21d2100L=200-78  \u21d2100L=122  \u2234L=122100=1.22cm","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>10>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Why are parabolic mirrors suitable for use in headlamps of vehicles?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Parabolic mirrors, due to their ability to efficiently collect and focus incoming parallel light rays, are suitable for use in vehicle headlamps, ensuring a concentrated and directed beam of light for improved visibility and reduced glare.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>10>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"Draw a ray diagram to illustrate the answer in 10(a)(i).","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>10>b>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SOUND WAVES : ECHOES AND REVERBERATION","question":"State two applications of echoes.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Sonar Systems: Sonar (Sound Navigation and Ranging) systems use echoes to determine the depth and location of objects underwater. A sound signal is emitted, and the time it takes for the signal to bounce off an object and return as an echo is used to calculate the distance to the object. Sonar is commonly used in marine navigation, fishing, and underwater mapping.    - Medical Imaging: In medical ultrasound imaging, echoes are used to create images of the interior of the body. High-frequency sound waves are directed into the body, and the echoes that bounce back from different tissues are used to generate detailed images of organs, blood vessels, and developing fetuses during pregnancy.    - Architectural Design: Architects and engineers use echoes to evaluate the acoustics of buildings and design spaces with optimal sound qualities. The controlled use of echoes can enhance the sound in concert halls, auditoriums, and theaters, providing a more enjoyable listening experience for audiences.    - Geological Surveys: Seismic surveys use echoes generated by controlled explosions or mechanical sources to map subsurface geological features. By analyzing the time it takes for seismic waves to reflect off different rock layers, geologists can infer the composition and structure of the Earth's subsurface.    - Surveying and Distance Measurement: Echoes are used in surveying and distance measurement equipment like total stations and laser rangefinders. A laser or light signal is emitted, and the time it takes for the light to bounce off a target and return is used to measure distances accurately.    - Echo Sounding in Navigation: In addition to sonar, echo sounding is used in navigation to determine water depth, especially in shallow or coastal areas. A sound signal is sent to the seabed, and the time it takes for the echo to return helps sailors and navigators avoid underwater hazards.    - Musical Effects: Musicians and audio engineers often use echoes and reverb effects in music production. These effects add depth and dimension to music by simulating the reflection of sound in different environments. Echoes and reverb are commonly used in recording studios, live concerts, and digital audio effects.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>10>b>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"SOUND WAVES : ECHOES AND REVERBERATION","question":"An observer standing at a point, P, on the same horizontal ground as the foot, H, of a tower shouts and 1.20 s later, he hears the echo. He then moved to another point, Q, 40 m from P, and shouts again but the echo was heard after 1.45 s. Calculate the:  I. distance between P and H;  II. speed of sound in air.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"I.s=2dt  Whentheobserverwasatpoint,P,  s=2xt=2x1.20---(i)  Whentheobserverwasatpoint,Q,  s=2(40 + x)t=2(40 + x)1.45---(ii)  Equatings:  \u21d22x1.2=2(40 + x)1.45  \u21d22x1.2=80 + 2x1.45  \u21d22.9x=1.2(80+2x)  \u21d22.9x=96+2.4x  \u21d22.9x-2.4x=96  \u21d20.5x=96  \u21d2x=960.5=192m  Therefore,thedistancebetweenPandHis192m.  II.Substitute(192m)forxinequation(i)  \u21d2s=2(192)1.2=320ms-1  Therefore,thespeedofsoundinairis320ms-1.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>10>c>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Define the term absolute refractive index of a medium.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The absolute refractive index of a medium is the ratio of the speed of light in vacuum to the speed of light in the medium. It is a measure of how much a medium slows down light.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>10>c>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A piece of coin falls accidentally into a tank containing two immiscible liquids A and B as illustrated in Fig. 10.0.     Calculate the displacement of the coin when viewed vertically from above.   [refractive index of A = 1.3, refractive index of B = 1.4]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Displacement(d)=Realdepth(R.D)-Apparentdepth(A.D)  n=R.DA.Dwherenistherefractiveindexofthemedium  A.D=R.Dn  So,d=R.D-R.Dn  \u2234d=R.D(1-1n)  Since the boundaries of the media are parallel, the total displacement of the coin is the sum of the displacements due to each of the media.    ForliquidA,displacement,d=40(1-11.3)=9.23cm  ForliquidB,displacement,d=8(1-11.4)=2.29cm  \u2234totaldisplacement=9.23+2.29=11.52cm  \u2234apparentpositionofthecoinis11.52cmfrombottom.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>11>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CONCEPTS OF ELECTRIC FIELD, ELECTRIC FIELD INTENSITY (POTENTIAL GRADIENT) AND ELECTRIC POTENTIAL.","question":"Define the electric potential at a point in an electric field.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Electric potential at a point is defined as the workdone in bringing unit positive charge from infinity to that point against the electrical forces of the field.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>11>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CHARGES","question":"An uncharged body, A, was charged electrostatically by a test charge, B, using the method of induction and the method of contact. State two differences between the two methods.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Process of Charging:    Induction: Involves redistributing charges within an uncharged body without direct contact with a charged object.  Contact: Requires direct physical contact with a charged object to transfer charges.    - Nature of Final Charge:    Induction: Results in a charge of opposite polarity to the charged object initially brought close.  Contact: Results in a charge of the same polarity as the charged object with which contact is made.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>11>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CIRCUIT","question":"An important precaution during an electricity experiment is to open the circuit when no readings are being taken. Give two reasons for the stated precaution.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Safety: Opening the circuit prevents current from flowing, which reduces the risk of electric shock. This is especially important when working with high voltages or currents.  - Conservation of battery power: If the circuit is left closed, current will continue to flow even when no readings are being taken. This can drain the battery and shorten its lifespan.  - Accurate readings: If the circuit is left closed, the current flowing through the circuit can cause the components to heat up. This can affect the accuracy of the readings.  - Protection of equipment: If the circuit is left closed, a surge of current could flow through the circuit if there is a fault. This could damage the equipment or even cause a fire.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>11>c>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : REACTANCE AND IMPEDANCE","question":"Fig. 11.0 is a circuit diagram in which a coil of inductance, L, and a resistor of resistance, R, are connected to a variable alternating source of frequency, f.    The table shows the square of the impedance, Z2; corresponding to each value of \u01922.    f2 / Hz2198.8400.0600.3800.9900.0Z2  / \u21262249.6400.0552.3702.3800.9    Write down the equation for Z in terms of f2, R2 and L2.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Z2 = R2 + XL2    Z2 = R2 + (2\u03c0fL)2    Z2 = R2 + 4\u03c02f2L2    Z2 = 4\u03c02f2L2 + R2    Z2 = 4\u03c02L2f2 + R2    \u2234 Z = &radic;4\u03c02L2f2 + R2&nbsp;","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>11>c>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : REACTANCE AND IMPEDANCE","question":"Fig. 11.0 is a circuit diagram in which a coil of inductance, L, and a resistor of resistance, R, are connected to a variable alternating source of frequency, f.    The table shows the square of the impedance, Z2; corresponding to each value of \u01922.    f2 / Hz2198.8400.0600.3800.9900.0Z2  / \u21262249.6400.0552.3702.3800.9  Plot a graph Z2 against f2 of and use it to determine the values of:  i. L  ii. R  [\u03c02 = 10]","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Fromtheequation:  Z2=4\u03c02L2f2+R2  Usingy=mx+c;y=Z2,x=f2  m=4\u03c02L2=slopeofthegraph   m=Z22 - Z12f22 - f12=700 - 200800 - 140  4\u03c02L2=500660  L2=500660\u00d714\u03c02=500660\u00d714 \u00d7 10(since\u03c02=10)  L2=0.0189  \u2234L=&radic;0.0189&nbsp;=0.138H=138mH  R2=y-intercept  R2=90  \u2234R=&radic;90&nbsp;=9.5\u2126","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"State the function of each of the following parts of a modern x-ray tube:    heater;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The heater, often referred to as the filament, is responsible for emitting electrons when heated.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"State the function of each of the following parts of a modern x-ray tube:  high tension source;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The high tension source, or high voltage generator, provides the high voltage necessary to accelerate the electrons emitted from the filament towards the anode (target) of the X-ray tube.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>a>iii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"State the function of each of the following parts of a modern x-ray tube:  cooling fins.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Cooling fins are designed to dissipate the heat generated during the operation of the X-ray tube.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>b>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"State one reason for each of the following design features of a modern x-ray tube:    the glass envelope is highly evacuated;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The x-ray tube is highly evacuated in order that the accelerated electrons can get to their target without losing much of their energy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>b>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"State one reason for each of the following design features of a modern x-ray tube:  the target is a metal of very high melting point;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The target is a metal of very high melting point to withstand the high temperature generated when the electrons strike the target.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>b>iii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"State one reason for each of the following design features of a modern x-ray tube:  the cooling fins are located outside the glass envelope.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The cooling fins are placed outside the glass envelope to ensure that the heat generated within the X-ray tube is efficiently transferred to the external environment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>c>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"In a nuclear fission reaction, a nuclide 23592U is bombarded with a neutron to produce 9336Kr and 14156Ba with additional neutrons, the energy involved in the process is Q.  [mass of  235U92 = 235.044 u, mass of 9336Kr = 91.898 u, mass of 14156Ba = 140.914 u,  mass of neutron = 1.009 u, 1 u = 1.66 x 10-27 kg, c = 3.0 \u00d7 108 ms-1]    Write down the balanced nuclear reaction equation for the process.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"23592U + 10n  \u2192  9336Kr + 14156Ba + 210n + Q","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>c>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"In a nuclear fission reaction, a nuclide 23592U is bombarded with a neutron to produce 9336Kr and 14156Ba with additional neutrons, the energy involved in the process is Q.  [mass of  235U92 = 235.044 u, mass of 9336Kr = 91.898 u, mass of 14156Ba = 140.914 u,  mass of neutron = 1.009 u, 1 u = 1.66 x 10-27 kg, c = 3.0 \u00d7 108 ms-1]  State with reason whether Q is absorbed or released in the process.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Energy, Q, is released because the total mass on the left hand side (reactant) is more than the total mass on the right hand side (product). So, the energy is released in the form of a reduction in total mass. This missing mass is known as the 'mass defect' and it accounts for the energy released. Also, it's an induced fission and nuclear fission is a process in which an unstable nucleus splits into two other lighter nuclei together with several neutrons and accompanied by release of energy.","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>c>iii","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"In a nuclear fission reaction, a nuclide 23592U is bombarded with a neutron to produce 9336Kr and 14156Ba with additional neutrons, the energy involved in the process is Q.  [mass of  235U92 = 235.044 u, mass of 9336Kr = 91.898 u, mass of 14156Ba = 140.914 u,  mass of neutron = 1.009 u, 1 u = 1.66 x 10-27 kg, c = 3.0 \u00d7 108 ms-1]  Calculate the value of Q in joules.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"E = \u2206mc2 where \u2206m is the mass defect.  Total mass on the LHS:  235.044 u + 1.009 u = 236.053 u  Total mass on the RHS:  91.898 u + 140.914 u + 2(1.009 u) = 234.83 u  Mass defect, \u2206m = 236.053 u - 234.83 u = 1.223 u  \u2206m = 1.223 \u00d7 1.66 \u00d7 10-27 = 2.03 \u00d7 10-27 kg  So,  E = 2.03 \u00d7 10-27 \u00d7 (3 \u00d7 108)2  = 1.827 \u00d7 10-10 J","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2023>PART 2>12>d","subject":"Physics","year":"2023","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"State three differences between nuclear fusion and nuclear fission.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Nuclear fusion involves the merging or combining of two light atomic nuclei to form a heavier nucleus, releasing energy in the process. This is the process that powers stars like the Sun while nuclear fission is the splitting of a heavy atomic nucleus into two or more lighter nuclei, accompanied by the release of energy. This process is used in nuclear power plants and atomic bombs.  - Nuclear fusion typically uses isotopes of light elements like hydrogen (e.g., deuterium and tritium) as fuel while nuclear fission commonly utilizes heavy elements like uranium-235 or plutonium-239 as fuel.  - Nuclear fusion reactions release much higher energy per unit mass than fission reactions while nuclear fission reactions release energy by the mass difference between the reactants and products, but the energy release per reaction is generally lower compared to fusion.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"}];